##############################################

DOCUMENT();

loadMacros(
  "PGstandard.pl",
  "MathObjects.pl",
  "PGML.pl",
  "contextFraction.pl",
  "PCCmacros.pl",
  "PGcourse.pl",
);

##############################################

Context("LimitedFraction");
Context()->flags->set(showMixedNumbers=>0);
Context()->flags->set(allowMixedNumbers=>1);
Context()->flags->set(requirePureFractions=>1);

do {
   $num1 = random(1,6,1);
   do {$den1 = random(7,12,1);} until (gcd($num1,$den1)==1);
   $frac1 = Fraction($num1,$den1);

   $num2 = random(1,6,1);
   do {$den2 = random(7,12,1);} until (gcd($num2,$den2)==1);
   $frac2 = Fraction($num2,$den2);

   $ans = ($frac1 * $frac2)->reduce;
   @temp = $ans->value;
   $numAns = $temp[0];
   $denAns = $temp[1];
} until ((gcd($num1,$den2)!=1)&&(gcd($num2,$den1)==1));

##############################################

TEXT(beginproblem());

BEGIN_PGML

Multiply these two fractions: [`` \frac{[$num1]}{[$den1]} \cdot \frac{[$num2]}{[$den2]} ``]

[@KeyboardInstructions("If needed, use an improper fraction in your answer. Don't use a mixed number.")@]**

    [_______]{$ans}

END_PGML

##############################################

$factor = gcd($num1,$den2);

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION

To multiply two fractions, simply multiply both numerators and both denominators. We have:

    [`` 
\begin{aligned}[t]
   &\phantom{{}=}\frac{[$num1]}{[$den1]} \cdot \frac{[$num2]}{[$den2]} \\
   &=\frac{[$num1]\div[$factor]}{[$den1]} \cdot \frac{[$num2]}{[$den2]\div[$factor]} \\
   &=\frac{[$num1/$factor]}{[$den1]} \cdot \frac{[$num2]}{[$den2/$factor]} \\
   &=\frac{[$num1/$factor] \cdot [$num2]}{[$den1] \cdot [$den2/$factor]} \\
   &= \frac{[$numAns]}{[$denAns]}
\end{aligned}
    ``]

Note that it's easier to reduce fractions before multiplying the numerators and denominators. Otherwise we have to deal with bigger numbers.

END_PGML_SOLUTION

ENDDOCUMENT();



